Boil a full #kettle{}.

Trim the @Pak Choi{1}(trimmed), then separate the leaves.

Peel and grate the @garlic{2%cloves}(peeled and grated) (or use a #garlic press{}).

== Noodles ==

Pour the boiled water into a large #saucepan{} on medium heat with @salt{1/2%tsp} and bring to a boil.

Add the @Egg Noodle Nest{125%grams} and pak choi to the water. Cook until tender, ~{4%minutes}.

Once cooked, drain in a #sieve{} and run under cold water to stop the noodles sticking together.

== Mince ==

Meanwhile, heat a drizzle of @oil{drizzle} in large #frying pan{} on medium-high heat.

Once hot, add the @Unconventional Plant-Based Burgers{2} to the pan.

Use a #spoon{} to mash into a mince-like texture as it cooks. Cook until browned, ~{5-6%minutes}. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

> IMPORTANT: Ensure they're piping hot throughout.

== Sauce ==

Add the @Thai Style Spice Mix{1%sachet} (add less if you'd prefer things milder), garlic and @Mangetout{80%grams} to the mince. Stir-fry for ~{30%seconds}.

Pour in the @Hoisin Sauce{64%grams}, @Teriyaki Sauce{50%grams}, @Soy Sauce{15%milliliters} and @Water for the Sauce{100%milliliters} and bring to a boil.

Reduce the heat slightly, then simmer until the sauce has thickened, ~{2-3%minutes}.

== Finishing ==

Once the sauce has thickened, toss the cooked noodles into the plant-based burger mixture until well combined.

Taste and season with @salt{} and @pepper{} if needed.

Add a splash of water if it's a little dry.

Share your sticky veggie mince noodles between your #bowls{}.

Enjoy!